								<a name="content"></a><p>As you learned in the <I>Desktop Taskbar</I> section, the Start button is usually located on the taskbar. It gives you access to the all of programs on your computer and allows you to start a program. However, in the <i>User Interface</i> section you learned about the controversy created when Microsoft removed the Start Button in Windows 8, replacing it with a list of programs in the Metro View. Windows 8.1 restored the Start Button, but id did not function like the provious Start Buttons functioned. The Start Button in Windoes 8.1 merely takes you to the Metro View, where you have the same list of programs as you do in Windows 8.</p>
                                <p>No matter which version of Windows you have, it&nbsp; is important to find out how to find programs on you computer. Once you find the program, you merely select it from the list to start it running. When you select a program, it will begin in its own window. You can have more than one program running at the same time and switch between them by clicking with your mouse on their individual buttons on the taskbar. Remember, each prgram that is running has its own window and a button on the taskbar, as you learned in the&nbsp;<i>Windows on Your Desktop</i> section.</p>
                                <p>Many keyboards have a Windows logo key&nbsp; <img class="img-wrap style1" src="images/computerbasics/WindowsLogoKey.png" alt="">you can press to get the beginning screen. </p>
                                <p>Let&#39;s locate the Start Button and do some hands on task to learn more.&nbsp; </p>
